s.\n\nAI can generate code quickly. Sometimes frighteningly quickly. But speed without clarity just accelerates entropy. We learned very early that delegating *decisions* to AI is a losing move.\n\nSo we reframed its role.\n\nAI is not a developer. It's not even a teammate. It's closer to an amplifier: whatever process you already have, AI will make it louder.\n\nThat led us to a simple rule that still holds:\n\n> **AI can help you move faster, but it never gets to decide where you're going.**\n\nOnce that boundary was explicit, fear dropped and usefulness went up.\n\n---\n\n## Quality starts before the first line of code\n\nOne of the first concrete changes was realizing that most bugs aren't implementation bugs. They're thinking bugs.\n\nSo instead of using AI after code existed, we started using it *before*.\n\nBefore opening an IDE, we'd ask questions like:\n\n- What assumptions are we making here?\n- What happens when this fails halfway?\n- Which parts of this logic are irreversible?\n\nAI is surprisingly good at being an annoying reviewer early in the process. Not because it's smarter, but because it's tireless. It will happily enumerate edge cases you forgot to consider while you were focused on the happy path.\n\nBy the time code was written, a large class of problems had already been surfaced, discussed, and either accepted or designed around.\n\n---\n\n## Code reviews became about thinking again\n\nAI didn't make code reviews less important. It made shallow reviews indefensible.\n\nIf a machine can point out formatting issues, unused variables, or obvious refactors, then humans shouldn't be spending their time there. Reviews had to move up a level.\n\nGradually, the center of gravity shifted. Good reviews stopped being about *what changed* and started being about *why this change makes sense*.\n\nPull requests that couldn't explain their reasoning felt incomplete, even if the code \"worked\". AI helped by summarizing diffs and flagging risky areas, but the final judgment stayed human, where it belongs.\n\n---\n\n## Testing stopped pretending to be one thing\n\nTesting culture often collapses under unrealistic expectations. Either everything must be perfectly tested, or testing quietly becomes optional.\n\nWe chose a third path: be explicit about what tests are for.\n\nAI writes a lot of our unit tests now. That's fine. They're fast, cheap, and good at catching regressions. But nobody confuses them with a specification of system behavior.\n\nThe tests that matter most — the ones that encode business invariants and critical flows — are still written deliberately, slowly, and with intent. Fewer of them, but trusted.\n\nThe clarity about *why* a test exists turned out to matter more than the test itself.\n\n---\n\n## Documentation finally stopped lagging behind reality\n\nDocumentation was always the first thing to be sacrificed under pressure. It felt expensive, and it aged badly.\n\nAI flipped the economics.\n\nInstead of writing docs as a separate task, we started generating them as a byproduct of work already being done: pull requests, design discussions, code changes.\n\nThe important shift wasn't automation. It was ownership. Documentation became something you reviewed, versioned, and argued about — just like code.\n\nWhen docs are allowed to be wrong, they quickly become irrelevant. When they're treated as part of the system, they start pulling their weight.\n\n---\n\n## The part tools can't fix\n\nAt some point it became obvious that none of this works without a cultural shift.\n\nAI doesn't create ownership. It exposes the lack of it.\n\nIf \"the AI wrote it\" becomes an acceptable answer, quality collapses. If clarity is optional, velocity becomes meaningless. If engineers are rewarded for output instead of understanding, the system will rot no matter how advanced the tools are.\n\nThis way of working only survives when teams are willing to slow down decisions that matter, and speed up everything else.\n\n---\n\n## What actually changed\n\nThe outcome wasn't explosive productivity gains or fewer meetings.\n\nWhat changed was the *feel* of the work.\n\nSystems became easier to reason about. Reviews became calmer. Knowledge spread more evenly. Senior engineers stopped acting as human caches of undocumented behavior.\n\nThis isn't the future of work. It's a correction. One that probably should have happened years ago.\n\nAnd like any real change, it's still unfinished.`,\n    date: \"2025-07-15\",\n    readTime: \"7 min read\",\n    tags: [\"ai\", \"code-quality\", \"testing\", \"documentation\", \"engineering-culture\"],\n    slug: \"new-way-of-working-ai-code-quality-testing-documentation\"\n  },",
            "old_string": "  {\n    id: \"2\",\n    title: \"A New Way of Working: AI, Code Quality, Testing, and Documentation\",\n    excerpt: \"Reducing cognitive load without sacrificing ownership. How AI becomes a force multiplier when used correctly.\",\n    content: `# A New Way of Working: AI, Code Quality, Testing, and Documentation\n\n*15 Jul 2025 — Mind of a Coder*\n*Reducing cognitive load without sacrificing ownership*\n\n---\n\nFor years we pretended that productivity was about writing more code, faster.\nThat illusion is finally collapsing under its own weight.\n\nModern engineering teams don't fail because they can't ship features.\nThey fail because they ship **entropy**: unreviewed code, fragile logic, tribal knowledge, and documentation that lies the moment it's written.\n\nThis \"new way of working\" didn't start as a manifesto.\nIt emerged as a survival mechanism.\n\n---\n\n## The Real Problem We Were Solving\n\nThe core issue wasn't velocity.\nIt was **cognitive overload**.\n\n- Codebases grow faster than shared understanding\n- Reviews degrade into \"LGTM\"\n- Tests exist but aren't trusted\n- Documentation is missing or obsolete\n- AI tools are used randomly, without ownership\n\nThe result is predictable: senior engineers become bottlenecks, juniors hesitate, and the system becomes harder to change every month.\n\nThe goal is simple to state and hard to execute:\n\n> **Reduce cognitive load while increasing code confidence.**\n\nAI is a lever. Not the solution.\n\n---\n\n## AI as a Force Multiplier, Not a Decision Maker\n\nThe biggest mistake teams make with AI is treating it like a junior developer you can delegate work to.\n\nThat's backwards.\n\nAI is closer to a **hyper-fast intern with infinite memory and zero accountability**.\n\nSo we redesigned the workflow around one non-negotiable rule:\n\n> **AI can generate, suggest, refactor — but never own decisions.**\n\nIn practice:\n\n- AI writes the **first draft**, never the final one\n- AI proposes tests, not testing strategy\n- AI explains code, humans validate correctness\n- AI accelerates feedback loops, not architectural choices\n\nThis framing removes fear and restores ownership.\n\n---\n\n## Code Quality Starts Before Code Exists\n\nTraditional pipelines treat quality as a downstream concern:\n\n\\`\\`\\`text\nwrite code → review → test → fix\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nThat's inefficient.\n\nWe shifted quality **left**, before implementation.\n\n### AI-Assisted Design Sketching\n\nBefore writing production code, we ask AI to:\n\n- Outline data models\n- Sketch function signatures\n- Identify edge cases\n- Propose failure modes\n\nNot to accept them blindly, but to **force early thinking**.\n\n\\`\\`\\`text\nPrompt:\n\"Given this requirement, list invariants, edge cases,\nand failure scenarios. Assume high scale and partial failure.\"\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nBy the time code is written, most conceptual bugs are already exposed.\n\n---\n\n## Code Reviews: From Gatekeeping to Reasoning\n\nAI didn't reduce the importance of code reviews.\nIt made **bad reviews unacceptable**.\n\nWe changed the review contract:\n\n- Reviews are about **reasoning**, not syntax\n- Every non-trivial PR must explain *why*, not just *what*\n- AI-generated code must be explicitly acknowledged\n\nA good PR description answers:\n\n- What problem does this solve?\n- Why this approach?\n- What alternatives were rejected?\n- What breaks if this changes?\n\nAI helps reviewers by summarizing diffs and highlighting risk areas.\nHumans decide if the logic stands.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Is Not Optional (But It's Not Sacred Either)\n\nHere's the uncomfortable truth: many teams write tests they don't trust.\n\nWe stopped pretending otherwise.\n\nTests are now **explicitly layered**:\n\n1. **AI-generated unit tests**\n   Fast, cheap, good at coverage — weak on intent\n\n2. **Human-written critical-path tests**\n   Focused on invariants and business rules\n\n3. **Contract and integration tests**\n   Treated as system documentation, not just safety nets\n\nAI is excellent at producing boilerplate:\n\n\\`\\`\\`text\nfor each edge_case:\n  given input\n  expect output\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nHumans decide **which edge cases matter**.\n\n---\n\n## Documentation as a Living Artifact\n\nDocumentation rots because writing it feels like a tax.\n\nAI changes that dynamic.\n\nWe flipped the process:\n\n- Documentation is generated **from code and PRs**\n- Engineers review docs the same way they review code\n- Docs are versioned, diffed, and owned\n\nTypical prompts:\n\n\\`\\`\\`text\n\"Explain this module as if onboarding a new engineer\"\n\"Summarize this PR in architectural terms\"\n\"What assumptions does this service make?\"\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nDocumentation stops being an afterthought and becomes a **byproduct of thinking**.\n\n---\n\n## The Cultural Shift (The Hard Part)\n\nTools don't change teams.\nExpectations do.\n\nThis way of working only functions if:\n\n- Ownership is non-negotiable\n- \"AI wrote it\" is never an excuse\n- Slower decisions are acceptable under uncertainty\n- Engineers are evaluated on clarity, not output volume\n\nAI amplifies both good and bad engineering habits.\nIf the culture is weak, AI accelerates the collapse.\n\n---\n\n## The Result\n\nThe outcome isn't magical productivity gains.\n\nIt's something better:\n\n- Fewer production surprises\n- Less heroism, more consistency\n- Code that can be explained, not just executed\n- Teams that scale without burning seniors\n\nThis isn't the future of work.\nIt's the correction we should have made years ago.\n\nAnd it's still a work in progress.`,\n    date: \"2025-07-15\",\n    readTime: \"8 min read\",\n    tags: [\"ai\", \"code-quality\", \"testing\", \"documentation\", \"engineering-culture\"],\n    slug: \"new-way-of-working-ai-code-quality-testing-documentation\"\n  },"
