 because they lacked skills, but because the blast radius of a mistake felt impossible to reason about.\n    43→\n    44→AI entered this picture almost by accident. At first as a curiosity, then as a toy, and eventually as something that forced us to rethink how work actually flows through a team.\n    45→\n    46→---\n    47→\n    48→## AI didn't change everything. It exposed everything.\n    49→\n    50→There's a lot of noise around AI replacing developers. In practice, what it really does is remove excuses.\n    51→\n    52→AI can generate code quickly. Sometimes frighteningly quickly. But speed without clarity just accelerates entropy. We learned very early that delegating *decisions* to AI is a losing move.\n    53→\n    54→So we reframed its role.\n    55→\n    56→AI is not a developer. It's not even a teammate. It's closer to an amplifier: whatever process you already have, AI will make it louder.\n    57→\n    58→That led us to a simple rule that still holds:\n    59→\n    60→> **AI can help you move faster, but it never gets to decide where you're going.**\n    61→\n    62→Once that boundary was explicit, fear dropped and usefulness went up.\n    63→\n    64→---\n    65→\n    66→## Quality starts before the first line of code\n    67→\n    68→One of the first concrete changes was realizing that most bugs aren't implementation bugs. They're thinking bugs.\n    69→\n    70→So instead of using AI after code existed, we started using it *before*.\n    71→\n    72→Before opening an IDE, we'd ask questions like:\n    73→\n    74→- What assumptions are we making here?\n    75→- What happens when this fails halfway?\n    76→- Which parts of this logic are irreversible?\n    77→\n    78→AI is surprisingly good at being an annoying reviewer early in the process. Not because it's smarter, but because it's tireless. It will happily enumerate edge cases you forgot to consider while you were focused on the happy path.\n    79→\n    80→By the time code was written, a large class of problems had already been surfaced, discussed, and either accepted or designed around.\n    81→\n    82→---\n    83→\n    84→## Code reviews became about thinking again\n    85→\n    86→AI didn't make code reviews less important. It made shallow reviews indefensible.\n    87→\n    88→If a machine can point out formatting issues, unused variables, or obvious refactors, then humans shouldn't be spending their time there. Reviews had to move up a level.\n    89→\n    90→Gradually, the center of gravity shifted. Good reviews stopped being about *what changed* and started being about *why this change makes sense*.\n    91→\n    92→Pull requests that couldn't explain their reasoning felt incomplete, even if the code \"worked\". AI helped by summarizing diffs and flagging risky areas, but the final judgment stayed human, where it belongs.\n    93→\n    94→---\n    95→\n    96→## Testing stopped pretending to be one thing\n    97→\n    98→Testing culture often collapses under unrealistic expectations. Either everything must be perfectly tested, or testing quietly becomes optional.\n    99→\n   100→We chose a third path: be explicit about what tests are for.\n   101→\n   102→AI writes a lot of our unit tests now. That's fine. They're fast, cheap, and good at catching regressions. But nobody confuses them with a specification of system behavior.\n   103→\n   104→The tests that matter most — the ones that encode business invariants and critical flows — are still written deliberately, slowly, and with intent. Fewer of them, but trusted.\n   105→\n   106→The clarity about *why* a test exists turned out to matter more than the test itself.\n   107→\n   108→---\n   109→\n   110→## Documentation finally stopped lagging behind reality\n   111→\n   112→Documentation was always the first thing to be sacrificed under pressure. It felt expensive, and it aged badly.\n   113→\n   114→AI flipped the economics.\n   115→\n   116→Instead of writing docs as a separate task, we started generating them as a byproduct of work already being done: pull requests, design discussions, code changes.\n   117→\n   118→The important shift wasn't automation. It was ownership. Documentation became something you reviewed, versioned, and argued about — just like code.\n   119→\n   120→When docs are allowed to be wrong, they quickly become irrelevant. When they're treated as part of the system, they start pulling their weight.\n   121→\n   122→---\n   123→\n   124→## The part tools can't fix\n   125→\n   126→At some point it became obvious that none of this works without a cultural shift.\n   127→\n   128→AI doesn't create ownership. It exposes the lack of it.\n   129→\n   130→If \"the AI wrote it\" becomes an acceptable answer, quality collapses. If clarity is optional, velocity becomes meaningless. If engineers are rewarded for output instead of understanding, the system will rot no matter how advanced the tools are.\n   131→\n   132→This way of working only survives when teams are willing to slow down decisions that matter, and speed up everything else.\n   133→\n   134→---\n   135→\n   136→## What actually changed\n   137→\n   138→The outcome wasn't explosive productivity gains or fewer meetings.\n   139→\n   140→What changed was the *feel* of the work.\n   141→\n   142→Systems became easier to reason about. Reviews became calmer. Knowledge spread more evenly. Senior engineers stopped acting as human caches of undocumented behavior.\n   143→\n   144→This isn't the future of work. It's a correction. One that probably should have happened years ago.\n   145→\n   146→And like any real change, it's still unfinished.`,\n   147→    date: \"2025-07-15\",\n   148→    readTime: \"7 min read\",\n   149→    tags: [\"ai\", \"code-quality\", \"testing\", \"documentation\", \"engineering-culture\"],\n   150→    slug: \"new-way-of-working-ai-code-quality-testing-documentation\"\n   151→  },\n   152→  {\n   153→    id: \"1\",\n   154→    title: \".NET 9 Telemetry: pushing logs and metrics to HELK with OpenTelemetry\",\n   155→    excerpt: \"Modern observability: sending .NET 9 telemetry to HELK with OpenTelemetry for logs, traces, and metrics.\",",
