          "text": "ora aggiungi questo:\n# Beyond Bronze–Silver–Gold: Rethinking Lakehouse Pipelines for Extreme Throughput\n\n*Exploring the intersection of software development, engineering best practices, and artificial intelligence.*\n\nFor years, the Bronze–Silver–Gold model has been the unquestioned gospel of data engineering.\nYou land raw data (Bronze), clean it (Silver), and reshape it for analytics (Gold). It looks elegant on slides.\n\nThen reality arrives with tens of millions of events per day, multi‑megabyte Protobuf payloads,\n1→150 fan‑outs, and upstream teams that “only changed one small field”.  \nThe diagram breaks before the pipeline does.\n\nAt high scale, the medallion pattern becomes a tax: more layers, more IO, more state,\nmore backfills, more operational risk.\n\nThis post explains why Bronze–Silver–Gold struggles under extreme throughput,\nand what a modern, streaming‑first Lakehouse architecture looks like instead.\n\n## Layered Pipelines Do Not Scale Linearly\n\nA typical setup looks like this:\n\n```\nKafka → Flink (Bronze) → Flink (Silver) → Flink (Gold) → Iceberg → Trino\n```\n\nEach layer multiplies cost:\nbytes processed, state size, failure modes, and recovery complexity.\nBackfills amplify pain across every layer.\n\nThe pattern assumes batch thinking.\nModern workloads are not batch‑shaped.\n\n## The Real Problem: Batch Thinking in a Streaming World\n\nBronze–Silver–Gold assumes:\n- bounded data\n- predictable schemas\n- controllable reprocessing windows\n\nStreaming workloads violate all three.\n\nBackpressure, micro‑files, runaway compactions and metadata overload\nare not bugs. They are symptoms of architectural mismatch.\n\n## Collapsing Layers, Not Responsibilities\n\nThe modern approach keeps responsibilities but removes physical layers:\n\n```\nKafka\n  → Flink (Ingest + Normalize + Diff)\n  → Iceberg (Single Source of Truth)\n  → Trino / Engines\n```\n\nInstead of copying data across layers,\nyou enrich records with metadata and expose multiple query views.\n\n## Silver Logic Without a Silver Table\n\nChange detection can live directly in the stream:\n\n```scala\n.keyBy(_.primaryKey)\n.process { rec =>\n  val newHash = xxHash(rec)\n  if (state.hash != newHash) {\n    emit(rec)\n    state.hash = newHash\n  }\n}\n```\n\nLess IO. Less storage. Less pain.\n\n## Fan‑Out Without Gold as a Physical Layer\n\nStreaming fan‑out does not require an intermediate table:\n\n```scala\nroute(record) match {\n  case \"network\"  => output(networkTag, record)\n  case \"software\" => output(softwareTag, record)\n}\n```\n\nDynamic Iceberg sinks handle the rest.\n\n## When Bronze–Silver–Gold Still Works\n\nIt still fits:\n- batch‑centric organizations\n- low throughput systems\n- conservative data platforms\n\nAt scale, however, it becomes friction.\n\n## Closing\n\nThe Lakehouse is maturing.\nMetadata, not layers, is the scaling lever.\n\nIf you are carrying three physical layers,\nask yourself whether they solve real problems—or just feel familiar.\n",
