            "old_string": "  {\n    id: \"5\",\n    title: \"Beyond Bronze–Silver–Gold: Rethinking Lakehouse Pipelines for Extreme Throughput\",\n    excerpt: \"Why the medallion pattern struggles at scale, and what a streaming-first Lakehouse architecture looks like instead.\",\n    content: `# Beyond Bronze–Silver–Gold: Rethinking Lakehouse Pipelines for Extreme Throughput\n\n*15 Nov 2025 — Mind of a Coder*\n*Why layered pipelines become a tax at extreme scale*\n\n---\n\nFor years, the Bronze–Silver–Gold model has been the unquestioned gospel of data engineering. You land raw data (Bronze), clean it (Silver), and reshape it for analytics (Gold). It looks elegant on slides.\n\nThen reality arrives with tens of millions of events per day, multi-megabyte Protobuf payloads, 1→150 fan-outs, and upstream teams that \"only changed one small field\". The diagram breaks before the pipeline does.\n\nAt high scale, the medallion pattern becomes a tax: more layers, more IO, more state, more backfills, more operational risk. This post explains why Bronze–Silver–Gold struggles under extreme throughput, and what a modern, streaming-first Lakehouse architecture looks like instead.\n\n---\n\n## Layered Pipelines Do Not Scale Linearly\n\nA typical setup looks like this:\n\n\\`\\`\\`text\nKafka → Flink (Bronze) → Flink (Silver) → Flink (Gold) → Iceberg → Trino\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nEach layer multiplies cost: bytes processed, state size, failure modes, and recovery complexity. Backfills amplify pain across every layer. The pattern assumes batch thinking. Modern workloads are not batch-shaped.\n\n---\n\n## The Real Problem: Batch Thinking in a Streaming World\n\nBronze–Silver–Gold assumes bounded data, predictable schemas, and controllable reprocessing windows. Streaming workloads violate all three.\n\nBackpressure, micro-files, runaway compactions and metadata overload are not bugs. They are symptoms of architectural mismatch.\n\n---\n\n## Collapsing Layers, Not Responsibilities\n\nThe modern approach keeps responsibilities but removes physical layers:\n\n\\`\\`\\`text\nKafka → Flink (Ingest + Normalize + Diff) → Iceberg (Single Source of Truth) → Trino / Engines\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nInstead of copying data across layers, you enrich records with metadata and expose multiple query views.\n\n---\n\n## Silver Logic Without a Silver Table\n\nChange detection can live directly in the stream:\n\n\\`\\`\\`scala\n.keyBy(_.primaryKey)\n.process { rec =>\n  val newHash = xxHash(rec)\n  if (state.hash != newHash) {\n    emit(rec)\n    state.hash = newHash\n  }\n}\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nLess IO. Less storage. Less pain.\n\n---\n\n## Fan-Out Without Gold as a Physical Layer\n\nStreaming fan-out does not require an intermediate table:\n\n\\`\\`\\`scala\nroute(record) match {\n  case \"network\"  => output(networkTag, record)\n  case \"software\" => output(softwareTag, record)\n}\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nDynamic Iceberg sinks handle the rest.\n\n---\n\n## When Bronze–Silver–Gold Still Works\n\nThe medallion pattern still fits batch-centric organizations, low throughput systems, and conservative data platforms. At scale, however, it becomes friction.\n\n---\n\n## Closing\n\nThe Lakehouse is maturing. Metadata, not layers, is the scaling lever. If you are carrying three physical layers, ask yourself whether they solve real problems — or just feel familiar.`,\n    date: \"2025-11-15\",\n    readTime: \"4 min read\",\n    tags: [\"data-engineering\", \"lakehouse\", \"flink\", \"iceberg\", \"streaming\"],\n    slug: \"beyond-bronze-silver-gold-lakehouse-pipelines\"\n  },"
